bject is added to the FetchBuffer, which maintains a queue of completed fetches ready for consumption.\n\nThe record parsing phase begins when FetchCollector.collectFetch() (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/FetchCollector.java:92) is called to convert buffered CompletedFetch objects into ConsumerRecords. For each CompletedFetch that needs to be processed, FetchCollector.fetchRecords() (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/FetchCollector.java:150) calls CompletedFetch.fetchRecords() (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/CompletedFetch.java:252), which iterates through the raw records in the response.\n\nEach individual Record from the RecordBatch is processed through CompletedFetch.parseRecord() (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/CompletedFetch.java:307), which deserializes the key and value bytes using the configured Deserializers and creates a ConsumerRecord object. This parseRecord method handles key/value deserialization, extracts headers, manages timestamps, and handles isolation level logic (e.g., filtering aborted transactions for READ_COMMITTED isolation).\n\nThe parsed ConsumerRecord objects are collected into a Fetch object (which is a container for ConsumerRecords grouped by partition) that is ultimately aggregated into a ConsumerRecords collection (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/ConsumerRecords.java:34) and returned to the user.\n\nThe entire chain integrates FetchSessionHandler (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/FetchSessionHandler.java) to manage incremental fetch sessions, FetchBuffer (clients/src/main/java/org/apache/kafka/clients/consumer/internals/FetchBuffer.java) to buffer completed fetches, and FetchMetricsAggregator to track metrics for bytes read and records parsed per partition."
